AB  - Medical robots offer a possibility to perform minimally invasive surgery, allowing patients to recover faster and improving the safety of operations. A lot of different medical robot simulation exist today, but they are not usable at any time because they are too close to a real surgical robot or lack of precision because they are only virtual. Therefore, the skills of surgeons decrease over time. This study aims to propose a new kind of simulation, mixing the advantages of both current physical and virtual simulations. We constructed a system including a haptic controller, a collaborative robotic arm, a forceps from the Da Vinci S, an actual surgical robot and an adaptor for the forceps. We then did a kinematic analysis of the system considering a Remote Center of Motion at the panel of the dry box to obtain the necessary Jacobian matrices to control the manipulator. We also convert the coordinate of the controller to the robot.
